<paragraph blockId="31.[264,1324,389,743]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,376,543,567]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<typeStatus box="[312,376,543,567]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Types</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
: The 
<typeStatus box="[444,538,543,566]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">syntypes</typeStatus>
in 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34991" box="[575,656,543,566]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34991" name="Hungarian Natural History Museum (Termeszettudomanyi Muzeum)" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">HNHM</collectionCode>
were destroyed in 
<number box="[866,922,543,566]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" value="1956.0">1956</number>
. Otherwise the only known 
<typeStatus box="[1230,1323,543,566]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">syntypes</typeStatus>
are the three females in 
<collectionCode box="[613,698,573,596]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">MSNM</collectionCode>
. None of these is perfect and the antennal flagellum is only present on one antenna of one of the two collected on 
<date box="[942,1103,602,625]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" value="1904-12-15" valueMax="1904-12-19" valueMin="1904-12-15">
<number box="[942,1009,602,625]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" value="17.0" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="15.0">15–19</number>
.xii. 
<number box="[1046,1103,602,625]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" value="1904.0">1904</number>
</date>
but this specimen is denuded and has tattered wings; the other of the same dates has tattered wing tips but the abdominal scaling is best preserved. This second of three specimens is here chosen as 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<typeStatus pageId="31" pageNumber="32">lectotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[446,525,691,714]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 22" captionStartId="30.[264,382,290,314]" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 22. Lectotype specimens of species of Bombyliidae referred to in Bezzi’s manuscript. 17 – 18, Tomomyza pictipennis (lectotype in MSNM). 17, male habitus. 18, wing. 19 – 20. Exoprosopa fuscescens Bezzi (lectotype in MSNM). 19, female habitus. 20, wing. 21 – 22. Exoprosopa contorta (lectotype in BMNH). 21, female habitus. 22, wing." pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[496,525,691,714]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
), since, although the third specimen has perfect wings, the abdominal vestiture is somewhat denuded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
